.TH NSAUDIT 1
.SH NAME
nsaudit \- namespace syntactic analysis for agent capability configurations
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nsaudit
[
.B -m
]
.I dir
.PP
.B nsaudit
[
.B -m
]
.I dir path
.PP
.B nsaudit
[
.B -m
]
.B -d
.I dirA dirB
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Nsaudit
is an advisory linter for Veltro agent capability configurations. Given
a caps directory (the same shape as a live
.I /tool
mount exposed by
.IR tools9p (8)),
it loads a per-tool authority manifest, computes the authority
inventory, applies a rule set, and prints a report.
.PP
.I Nsaudit
enforces nothing. Namespace restriction is enforced at runtime by
.IR nsconstruct ,
.IR forkns ,
.IR nodevs ,
.IR cowfs ,
and
.IR wallet9p .
.I Nsaudit
is a pre-flight review that answers a single question:
.IP
.B
what does this namespace configuration actually allow the agent to do?
.LP
A caps value that passes
.I nsaudit
is
.B not
"safe". It is free of the authority compositions
.I nsaudit
knows to check for. The boundary is deliberate.
.SS Modes
With one positional argument,
.I nsaudit
prints a full report: authority inventory, reads_fs/writes_fs paths
with reversibility annotations, and any rule violations.
.PP
With two positional arguments, the second is a filesystem path;
.I nsaudit
prints whether that path is reachable for reads or writes and via
which cap it is granted (or, if denied, the closest granted prefix).
.PP
With
.B -d
and two positional arguments,
.I nsaudit
prints the difference in authorities between the two caps directories.
This is the PR-review mode: *"what did this change add or remove?"*
.SS Options
.TP
.B -d
Diff mode. Requires two positional arguments (before and after caps dirs).
.TP
.B -m
Machine-readable mode. Emits
.IR ndb (6)
records, one per entry, which can be parsed by
.IR ndb/query (8)
or by any tool that reads attribute=value files. This is the stable
machine interface; use it in scripts and when consumed by other agents.
.SH "CAPS DIRECTORY FORMAT"
A caps directory is a directory of scalar files matching the shape
.IR tools9p (8)
exposes at
.BR /tool :
.PP
.B
.nf
	dir/tools               one tool name per line
	dir/paths               one path grant per line
	dir/meta/role           "toplevel" or "child"
	dir/meta/xenith         "1" or "0"
	dir/meta/actid          integer or "-1"
	dir/meta/nodevs         "set" or "unset"
.fi
.PP
For live audit, point
.I nsaudit
at
.BR /tool .
For hypothetical analysis or CI fixtures, construct a mock directory
of the same shape.
.SH "AUTHORITY MANIFEST"
The per-tool authority manifest lives at
.BR /lib/veltro/nsaudit/authorities/ .
One
.IR ndb (6)
file per tool. Each entry must start with
.B tool=NAME
and must list an
.B authorities
attribute containing the space-separated set of authority axes the
tool grants. Optional attributes:
.B description ,
.B irreversible ,
.BR notes .
.PP
.B
.nf
	tool=exec
		description='Execute a shell command via sh.dis'
		authorities='spawns_proc execs_code reads_fs writes_fs dials_net'
		irreversible='spawns_proc writes_fs dials_net'
		notes='Force multiplier; scope limited by caps.shellcmds.'
.fi
.PP
Adding a tool to
.I appl/veltro/tools
means adding a manifest file. Missing manifest entries are a fatal
error; use
.I nsaudit -k
(not yet implemented) to treat unknown tools as maximally
authorized. Fail-loud is the default because silent fallback is how
manifests rot.
.SH "RULE SET"
Rules live at
.BR /lib/veltro/nsaudit/rules/ .
One
.IR ndb (6)
file per rule. Each entry has:
.TP
.B rule
Rule name in SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE.
.TP
.B severity
.B high ,
.B medium ,
or
.BR info .
.TP
.B require
Space-separated list of conditions, all of which must hold for the
rule to fire. Condition syntax:
.IP
.in +4
.B role=VALUE
matches
.B meta/role
.br
.B nodevs=VALUE
matches
.B meta/nodevs
.br
.B has_tool_NAME
tool is present in
.B tools
.br
.I authority_name
authority is present in the inventory
.in -4
.TP
.B andone
Optional. Space-separated list of conditions; at least one must hold.
.TP
.B message
Human-readable description of what the rule catches.
.TP
.B fix
Suggested remediation.
.PP
Example (detects the NODEVS gap for top-level agents):
.PP
.B
.nf
	rule=DEVICE_GATE_BYPASS
		severity=high
		require='role=toplevel nodevs=unset'
		message='top-level caps grants kernel device attach ...'
		fix='add sys->pctl(Sys->NODEVS, nil) after FORKNS'
.fi
.SH "MACHINE-READABLE OUTPUT"
With
.BR -m ,
.I nsaudit
emits one
.IR ndb (6)
record per line. Records are distinguished by their first attribute:
.PP
.B
.nf
	nsaudit=caps       the caps header (dir, role, nodevs, actid, xenith)
	authority=NAME     one authority axis present in the inventory
	reads_fs=PATH      one granted reads_fs path
	writes_fs=PATH     one granted writes_fs path with reversibility tag
	violation=RULE     one rule violation with severity, message, fix
	reach=PATH         reach query header
	nsaudit=diff       diff header
	removed=NAME       authority removed in diff
	added=NAME         authority added in diff
.fi
.PP
The output is parseable by
.IR ndb/query (8):
.PP
.B
.nf
	; nsaudit -m /tool > /tmp/audit
	; ndb/query -f /tmp/audit -a violation
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
Full report on a fixture:
.PP
.B
.nf
	; nsaudit /tests/nsaudit-fixtures/minimal
.fi
.PP
Ask whether the agent can read a specific file:
.PP
.B
.nf
	; nsaudit /tool /n/local/Users/pdfinn/project/secrets.txt
.fi
.PP
Compare two configurations:
.PP
.B
.nf
	; nsaudit -d /tool.old /tool.new
.fi
.PP
Pipe machine output to a query:
.PP
.B
.nf
	; nsaudit -m /tool > /tmp/audit
	; ndb/query -f /tmp/audit -a authority
.fi
.SH EXIT STATUS
.I Nsaudit
exits nonzero when any
.B high
severity violation is present. This makes
.I nsaudit
suitable as a CI gate: any fixture whose expected state includes no
high violations will fail the build if one is introduced.
.SH FILES
.TF /lib/veltro/nsaudit/rules
.TP
.B /lib/veltro/nsaudit/authorities
Per-tool authority manifest, one
.IR ndb (6)
file per tool.
.TP
.B /lib/veltro/nsaudit/rules
Rule set, one
.IR ndb (6)
file per rule.
.TP
.B /lib/veltro/nsaudit/suppressions
Named, dated suppressions of specific (fixture, rule) pairs with
expiry dates. Expired suppressions fail CI.
.TP
.B /tests/nsaudit-fixtures
Committed caps fixtures for CI gating. Each has an
.B expected.ns
snapshot.
.SH SOURCE
.B /appl/cmd/nsaudit.b
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.IR attrdb (2),
.IR ndb (6),
.IR ndb/query (8),
.IR tools9p (8),
.IR sys-pctl (2),
.I /appl/veltro/SECURITY.md
.SH BUGS
.I Nsaudit
cannot detect prompt injection propagation, cannot reason about
semantic reversibility, and is only as sound as the per-tool manifest.
A lying manifest entry is undetectable without the runtime
ground-truth check (not yet implemented). See
.I /appl/veltro/SECURITY.md
for the full statement of what the tool cannot answer.
.PP
The tool does not yet consult
.I suppressions
when computing exit status. Adding a suppression does not suppress
exit nonzero on a high-severity finding.
.PP
Unknown tool names (no manifest entry) are a fatal error, without
an override. A
.B -k
(permissive) flag is planned.
